    print("  Orthogonality explains a minority of Muon's advantage in nonlinear nets.")
elif relu_recovery > 0:
    print("  *** MINIMAL TRANSFER (0-20%) ***")
    print("  The position penalty (||W^TW-I||) provides negligible benefit.")
else:
    print("  *** NO TRANSFER / PENALTY HURTS ***")
    print("  The orthogonality penalty is COUNTERPRODUCTIVE in nonlinear nets.")
    print("  Forcing weights toward orthogonality conflicts with what the")
    print("  nonlinear net needs (asymmetric singular values to match data structure).")
    print()
    print("  KEY INSIGHT: In nonlinear nets, Muon's advantage comes from:")
    print("    1. DIRECTIONAL benefit: ortho(grad) gives steepest descent on Stiefel manifold")
    print("    2. SPECTRAL equalization: all singular value directions get equal step size")
    print("    3. NOT from keeping W near I (which the penalty tries to do)")
    print()
    print("  The mechanism is qualitatively different from the deep linear case:")
    print("    - Linear: gauge symmetry exists, penalty removes redundant directions -> helps")
    print("    - Nonlinear: no gauge symmetry, penalty restricts useful degrees of freedom -> hurts")

# =============================================================================
# Context about the difference with P16
# =============================================================================
print("\n\n" + "-" * 70)
print("CONTEXT: Why this differs from P16's 96.3%")
print("-" * 70)
print("""
  P16 tested a different penalty: gauge VELOCITY (||Q_t - Q_{t-1}||^2_F).
  This experiment tests gauge POSITION (||W^TW - I||^2_F).

  These are fundamentally different:
    - Velocity penalty: "don't change gauge direction between steps"
      -> Allows W to be far from orthogonal, just prevents CHANGES
      -> Works by smoothing the optimization trajectory

    - Position penalty: "keep W close to the orthogonal group"
      -> Constrains the manifold where W lives
      -> Can conflict with the optimal solution (target may need non-orthogonal W)

  The position penalty fails because:
    1. The TARGET MATRIX is not orthogonal (it's random), so the optimal W_product
       must have non-unit singular values
    2. Forcing individual layers to be orthogonal constrains the product too much
    3. In nonlinear nets, the activation functions break the gauge symmetry entirely

  P16's velocity penalty succeeds because it doesn't constrain WHERE W is,
  only HOW FAST the gauge changes — this is compatible with any target.
""")

